    "Tony W. Cartledge": "The Common and the Holy. There is a delightful interplay\nbetween the words \u201choly\u201d(qo\u00afdes\u02c7 ) and \u201ccommon\u201d (h.ol) in 21:4-\nv. 2).\nThe text describes David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s new allies as being made of \u201ceveryone\u201d\nwho was \u201cin distress\u201d (lit., \u201cbitter in spirit\u201d), who was in debt, and\nwho was discontented. This suggests that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` gave hope to a\nband of economically challenged people who wished to oppose the\nmore wealthy and politically powerful populace (cf. Saul\u2019s taunt in\n22:7). Elsewhere, the phrase \u201cbitter in spirit\u201d is used to describe\n[v_1Sa_1_10] Hannah\u2019s feelings about her childlessness (1 Sam 1:10), the grief of\nthe men of Ziklag over the kidnapping of their families (1 Sam\n30:6), and David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s own concern over the loss of his city, compared\n[v_2Sa_17_8] to a mother bear bereft of her cubs (2 Sam 17:8).\nHaving suffered great loss himself, David `[char_David_Rut_4]` becomes the hero and\nleader of others who have experienced deprivation, disenchant-\nment, and discontent. The text numbers David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s followers at 400,\nthough they would quickly swell to include at least 600 fighting\nmen (23:13; 25:13; 27:2; 30:9, 10). For attentive readers, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s\nposition as the leader of an outlaw army may call to mind Jephthah\nof Gilead, who led his ragtag army to victory over the Ammonites\nand so became a \u201cjudge\u201d in Israel (Judg 11).\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` in Moab, 22:3-5\nThe unusual interlude in 22:3 suggests that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` had negotiated\nsome sort of alliance with the king of Moab. On the surface this\nseems strange, because Israel and Moab were perennial enemies.\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s friendlier connection could have grown from an interna-\ntional political agenda: It would be in the Moabite king\u2019s desire to\nfoment trouble in Israel by assisting David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, who had gained a rep-\nutation as a rebel leader. Saul had once defeated Moab in battle\n(14:47). The king had no way of knowing that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` would later\n[v_2Sa_8_2] do the same thing (2 Sam 8:2; 1 Chr 18:2).\nA second suggested scenario is that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` appealed to a family\nconnection. According to the genealogy of Ruth\n4:18-22, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s great-grandmother was Ruth,\na Moabite. Indeed, some Jewish traditions held\nthat Ruth was of royal blood. [Princess Ruth?]\nThus, when David `[char_David_Rut_4]` sought safe haven for his\nparents, he could have claimed family relations\nin high places.\n[v_1Sa_21_10] 1 Samuel 21:10\u201322:23\n262\nPrincess Ruth?\nSome traditions hold that Ruth was of\nroyal blood, that she and Orpah were\nboth daughters of King Eglon. One tradition even\nholds that Orpah remarried and became the\nancestress of the Philistine giant Goliath! (\u00c9tan\nLevine, The Aramaic Version of Ruth [Rome:\nBiblical Institute Press, 1973], 55, 486).\n263\n[v_1Sa_21_10] 1 Samuel 21:10\u201322:23\nThe reference to Mizpeh of Moab is somewhat\nproblematic, since it is mentioned only in 1\nSamuel 22:3. [Mizpeh of Moab?] The word mis.p\u00e2h\nmeans \u201cwatchtower.\u201d It could have referred to a\nMoabite outpost where David `[char_David_Rut_4]` parleyed with royal\nrepresentatives, or it may have been an otherwise\nobscure royal city.\nThe location of the \u201cstronghold\u201d in vv. 4-5 is\nuncertain. The Syriac version reads \u201cMizpeh\u201d\ninstead of \u201cstronghold,\u201d suggesting that David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\nstayed in Moab for a while, and the words of Gad in\n2. Know When to Retreat. There is a difference between running\nfrom problems and retreating to find the safety and strength\nneeded to confront those problems. When David `[char_David_Rut_4]` left the priests of\nNob and made his way toward a place of temporary safety, he was\ntaking initiative for his own well-being, though God continued to\nwork in his life. The fact that King Achish rejected David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s request\nfor political asylum and declared him fit for an insane asylum is\nimmaterial. David `[char_David_Rut_4]` was making the effort to regain control of his\nlife\u2014even if he had to feign being out of control in order to do it!\nFurthermore, even David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s apparent failure at Gath may have\nhelped pave the way for his later success in forging a temporary\nalliance with the Philistine king (ch. 27).\nWhen life seems overwhelming, it is wise to retreat to a place of\nsafety where we can find relief and release. Sometimes the best\nthing we can do is let go of our public persona and allow ourselves\nto act in ways that seem crazy or uncharacteristic for us. There is a\ngreat catharsis to be found in a good vacation for the workaholic,\nor in a structured retreat for the \u201ccontrol freak.\u201d Sometimes the\nbest way to regain control of our minds is to step outside of our\nnormal thinking processes and see life from a different perspective.\nSurely David `[char_David_Rut_4]` did not journey to Gath with that intention\u2014his\n\u201cretreat\u201d did not turn out as planned\u2014but he was cunning enough\nto shift into survival mode, and he learned from the process.\nv. 2), though it did not satisfy his fighting men, who\nargued that they were frightened enough while hiding in the woods\nand desired no open conflict (\nv. 2)\nSaul came to the sheepfolds beside the road. (\nv. 2)\nSaul camped beside the road. ("
