    "Tony W. Cartledge": "Rely on Friends and Family. Once David `[char_David_Rut_4]` had escaped from the\nGittites and found refuge at Adullam, his first order of business was\nto seek the support of his family, and to broaden his network of\nfriends. This became a mutual support system, for David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s family\nand newfound friends needed him as much as he needed them.\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s parents and brothers would not have been safe from Saul\u2019s\npredations as long as David `[char_David_Rut_4]` remained unaccounted for. There may\nhave been lingering tension between David `[char_David_Rut_4]` and his brothers over\nthe fact that Samuel had anointed him rather than one of the older\nbrothers (16:6-13). The prelude to the story of Goliath implies a\ncontinued rivalry between the brothers (17:28-29). The brothers\nmay have resented David `[char_David_Rut_4]` even more for incurring Saul\u2019s wrath and\nthus bringing them into jeopardy, but none of this is evident in\n22:1, where all of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s family comes to him, or in 22:3, where\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` requests a safe haven for his parents with the king of Moab.\nPerhaps there is no greater source of hurt\u2014or of healing\u2014than\nour families. None of us grows up without some reason to com-\nplain of unfair treatment. Unfortunately, many persons carry\nteenage grudges into later life and miss out on the great strength\nthat can be found in loving family relationships. Others learn to\nput past offenses behind them and build better families for the\nfuture. Some families are so dysfunctional that they may never be\nredeemed, but the potential reward is worth the effort.\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` also took the initiative to create a new network of friends,\ndrawing to himself \u201ceveryone who was in distress and everyone\nwho was in debt and everyone who was discontented.\u201d David `[char_David_Rut_4]` was\nnot the only person to experience loss or deprivation. The social\nchanges brought about by the monarchy had brought hardship to\nmany. Together with David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, these 400 (and soon more) persons\nbecame a veritable support group. [Support Groups ] Alone, their bit-\nterness of spirit had accomplished nothing. Together, their mutual\n[v_1Sa_21_10] 1 Samuel 21:10\u201322:23\n268\n269\n[v_1Sa_21_10] 1 Samuel 21:10\u201322:23\nconcerns gelled them into a group that had hope and strength and\na future. Surely this group tested David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s leadership skills, but he,\nlike his new army, became stronger for the experience.\nv. 3). To assuage their doubts, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\nonce again sought Yahweh\u2019s will, perhaps in a more public forum,\nand received the answer (\nv. 3; also\nv. 3)\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s men insisted that Yahweh was providing an\nopportunity to kill Saul. (\nv. 3)\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` and company were sitting in the desert. (\nv. 3)\nAbishai argued that God was providing an opportunity to kill\nSaul. ("
